<paragraph id="61A7587DB7F51E71DD0B7C9C38877980" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Coloane, 20 May 1994, MW Ng (CIAM); Parque Natural de Taipa Grande, 24 May 2020 5:36, Wai Chan (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70479773); ibidem 8 May 2021 17:07, Kit Chang (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/77868888); Great Taipa, 8 May 2021, perched on leaves on road margin, R Perissinotto &amp; Lynette Clennell (IZCAS).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D3706049EF954413A3B257416FE13269" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="BD002DF5D40AA1425A56FAD4DF4F95A5" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F59BBB82BFD1EC3D96203D79FA6E2ACD" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<bibRefCitation id="16B30D044A8EEF9D9072CE151EC5BC25" author="Easton, ER" journalOrPublisher="University of Macau Publications Centre, Macau" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" refId="B38" refString="Easton, ER, 1993. The insects of Macau. University of Macau Publications Centre, Macau" title="The insects of Macau." year="1993">Easton (1993)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species as &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="BE49989B62714D0CA357D0594B75A51F" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Chelidonium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chelidonium sinense" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinense">
<emphasis id="00ACD3012F54BEF58647CD75348BCE2F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Chelidonium sinense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hope)&quot; but it seems most likely that the main species involved in his observations was actually 
<taxonomicName id="09725E4FB21D61E707B1D7F8688EB143" genus="C." lsidName="C. argentatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="argentatum">
<emphasis id="CF5743DEF595B716FA21AFC15E739C30" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">C. argentatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and not 
<taxonomicName id="0BD15DBAD6FAEEE546C8180B4B15D26F" baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1842" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Polyzonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Polyzonus sinensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="FCA4E21C4D7E126C320F3E1D19E7BACA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Polyzonus sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, given the laterally expanded metatibia and short tarsal segments exhibited by the typical specimen illustrated in his work (
<bibRefCitation id="A0A10EBAC30F40090BB566C669B9DA25" author="Easton, ER" journalOrPublisher="University of Macau Publications Centre, Macau" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" refId="B38" refString="Easton, ER, 1993. The insects of Macau. University of Macau Publications Centre, Macau" title="The insects of Macau." year="1993">Easton 1993</bibRefCitation>
: 47). During the current census, 
<taxonomicName id="A72966B4DA2077B86974FAE1B35E76ED" genus="P." lsidName="P. sinensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="D085A0FF15C8EF65000B1788BD8C82EB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">P. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was only observed on three occasions and always on Great Taipa Hill. The total length of these specimens varies between 23 and 26 mm, while their maximum width lies in the range of 5-6 mm. Adult specimens appear to have their peak of activity in May and have so far only been observed feeding on flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="3B6E010EF3425AC7BFEEA2AD49C2DAD7" authorityName="Gardn &amp; Champ" authorityYear="1849" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Theaceae" genus="Schima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Schima superba" order="Guttiferales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="superba">
<emphasis id="8ACFEE9DD3C0DF115062538D4848387F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Schima superba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
during the hottest part of the day. 
<bibRefCitation id="B15D175EFF35D2D510A241E7422AD311" author="Yiu, V" journalOrPublisher="Hong Kong Entomological Society, Hong Kong" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" refId="B161" refString="Yiu, V, 2009. Longhorn Beetles of Hong Kong. Insect Fauna of Hong Kong, Fascicle 1. Hong Kong Entomological Society, Hong Kong" title="Longhorn Beetles of Hong Kong. Insect Fauna of Hong Kong, Fascicle 1." year="2009">Yiu (2009)</bibRefCitation>
reported that in Hong Kong the larvae of this species bore into 
<taxonomicName id="E6C4A75ADED07028D01D1904C0A45A08" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rutaceae" genus="Citrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Citrus" order="Rutales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="54CA38063F86D3BF1CE547C4DA591877" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Citrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plants and 
<bibRefCitation id="2AA18140713396DA34FC60A16A68603A" author="Hua, L-Z" journalOrPublisher="List of Chinese Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="1 - 612" refId="B68" refString="Hua, L-Z, 2002. List of Chinese Insects. Zhongshan (Sun Yat-Sen) University Press, Guangzhou. List of Chinese Insects 2: 1 - 612" title="List of Chinese Insects. Zhongshan (Sun Yat-Sen) University Press, Guangzhou." volume="2" year="2002">Hua (2002)</bibRefCitation>
also listed 
<taxonomicName id="4AE6D10A2FAD18EE90BEB19659FEFCA8" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acacia" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF3A44B0CF460E4D91DAA020A3B286C9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. as host plants in its broader distribution range.
</paragraph>
<caption id="18CA57C100CE88DCF46536ADA085AD8C" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1049.65558.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/569387" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" start="Figure 9" startId="F9">
<paragraph id="0A1E6F5DC8285181CD75D2888B48B3E7" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis id="0A3C3116E5A19E262397297F9E19178C" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Figure 9.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="5EC086D93B7C2B5A275208B9A5EA55EB" baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1842" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Polyzonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Polyzonus sinensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="D520F15944033574E388F16EB6E2B530" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Polyzonus sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hope, 1842): dorsal (
<emphasis id="8E58DB83CA3B0FD258CEBFCDE4D222C6" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">A</emphasis>
) and lateral (
<emphasis id="922B10C9E83F7C208F8BF92B270444A1" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">B</emphasis>
) views of specimen observed on Great Taipa Hill on 8 May 2021 (photographs: LC).
</paragraph>
